[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Esse","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik.","Norwegian: habitational name from the farmstead Ese in Sogn of unexplained etymology, or Esse in Telemark, named with Old Norse <i>æsin</i> ‘hill’ + <i>-e</i> from <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’.","German: variant of   Ess  , or a topographic name from the river name Esse in Hesse."],"variants":[{"name":"Ess","meanings":["North German: topographic name for someone living on or owning land that was waterlogged or partly surrounded by water, from Middle Low German <i>es</i> ‘swamp, water’.","Swiss German: from the topographic name <i>Ess</i> ‘grazing area, pasture’.","Swiss German: from a vernacular short form of the personal name   Oswald  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":0,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":13,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":22,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Esse was born about 1315, in Sherford, Devon, England, her father, Oliver Ashe de Esse, was 36 and her mother, Lady Emma D'Esse Cruys, was 46. She had at least 2 sons with Richard Hals. She died in 1373, in her hometown, at the age of 59."},"et":{"about 1315–1373":"umbes 1315–1373","1292–1327":"1292–1327","1312–Male":"1312–Surnud","1315–1373":"1315–1373","1327–1400":"1327–1400","1297–1370":"1297–1370","1321–Male":"1321–Surnud","1323–1405":"1323–1405","1280–1332":"1280–1332","1270–1365":"1270–1365","1297":"1297","1373":"1373","1370":"1370","1270":"1270","1292":"1292","abt 1321":"umbes 1321","1280":"1280","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1323":"1323","1400":"1400","1312":"1312","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","1321":"1321","about 1315":"umbes 1315","about 1323":"umbes 1323","Mar 1365":"märts 1365","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1405":"1405","Sherford, Devon, England":"Sherford, Devon, England","Westho Parish, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Plymouth, Devon, England":"Plymouth, Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 131